result.name: Tim Ho Wan

reviews.text:
The food here is quite good. Try different things until you will find what you like. But the service is probably the worst l have ever seen. Yelling at elderly citizens is quite normal here. Forget about "thank you" and "please". It's actually quite fun to come here and analyse worker's behaviour. I feel like going to the zoo...

Food: 8/10
Service: 1/10

The food is really good - as expected. Can you get better Dim Sum somewhere else? Of course. But this is the best for the most accessible Dim Sum if you're swinging by HK and looking to get something quick and fast. 

Seating is quite cramped though and they WILL shove you onto tables with other people if there is vacancy.

5 Stars off of the food and accessibility of the good food alone.

Deciding between 4 or 5 stars but decided on 5star because I came here 3yrs ago and the food is still consistently good. Better than average yum cha and price is cheap! Saw a Caucasian lady asking the owner’s daughter (presumably because the daughter spoke English) if she could take some of the chili sauce home and the owner just poured a small container for her. Small gesture like this is so nice/different to see.

Michelin-starred. Fast food. Before Tim Ho Want, who knew these two labels could describe the same eatery? Was here with colleague. Try their recommendations, try their items that aren't explicitly recommended. It's all good. For the vegetarians, it may look like there isn't much on the menu for you -- and you'd be right, actually. But I've always managed to get a full meal while eating at THW's. Which brings me to this- they are not just in Hong Kong. So, maybe you could look for them around the corner, whichever dimension you're staying in? For those with the elephant of an appetite, or the appetite of a strictly vegan elephant, there might be other pecking spots for you nearby?

It is a tourist attraction and no more than that. It is not an authentic dim sum experience and you will be sitting next to really annoying tourists, which it isn't the restaurant's fault really. The restaurant just want you to finish the food as quickly as possible to turn tables for the huge line outside.
